  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane auctions run quickly. The whole event is often over in under thirty minutes, but the decisions made in that window can significantly affect your outcome. Sellers who understand the mechanics of auction day are better placed to respond calmly and make good calls in real time. The following is a plain-language walkthrough of what actually happens.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The day before: confirming your reserve</h2>
      <p>Your agent will typically sit down with you the afternoon or evening before auction to confirm your reserve price. The reserve is the minimum price at which you are willing to sell. Once the bidding reaches or exceeds the reserve, the property is declared 'on the market' and will sell to the highest bidder when the hammer falls.</p>

      <p>The reserve conversation should be informed by the campaign data your agent has collected: how many groups inspected, who bid at earlier open homes, and what price feedback has come back from genuine buyers. Your agent's job is to give you an honest recommendation based on that data, not to tell you what you want to hear. The reserve stays strictly confidential between you and your agent. If buyers know the reserve, there is no reason for them to bid above it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The morning of auction day</h2>
      <p>Many Brisbane auctions hold a final open home on the morning of auction day, typically for thirty minutes before the scheduled start. This gives buyers who have already inspected a final walkthrough and allows any last-minute interest to be captured. Your property should be in the same presentation-ready condition it was for the campaign open homes.</p>

      <p>As a seller you do not need to be at the property during the open home or the auction itself. Many sellers watch from a discreet distance or wait nearby with their agent. Being visibly present on the floor can make buyers less comfortable bidding openly, so if you do attend, stay back and let the auctioneer and agent work.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The auctioneer briefing</h2>
      <p>Before the auction opens publicly, your agent and the auctioneer will review the registered bidders. In Queensland, buyers must register before they can bid. Registration involves providing identification and sometimes a deposit or proof of pre-approval, depending on the terms of the auction. The number of registered bidders gives you an early read on competition: three or more registered bidders in the room suggests a competitive auction.</p>

      <p>The auctioneer will also review the bidding rules and confirm the terms with your agent one final time. The auctioneer acts on your instructions during the auction, including whether to accept vendor bids.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Opening the auction</h2>
      <p>The auctioneer opens proceedings by announcing the property, the terms of sale, and inviting opening bids. Some bidders will open immediately. Others will hold back to watch the room. If the room is slow to start, the auctioneer can make a vendor bid to get bidding moving. A vendor bid is a bid made on the seller's behalf by the auctioneer, and it must be announced as such. Vendor bids are legal in Queensland but can only be made while the property is still below the reserve.</p>

      <p>Once bidding begins in earnest, the auctioneer controls the pace. They may accept bids in increments they choose and can reject a bid if they consider it not in good faith. The rhythm of a well-run Brisbane auction is typically fast and confident: the auctioneer calling bids, working the room, and building momentum.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the reserve is reached</h2>
      <p>Once bidding reaches your reserve, the auctioneer declares the property 'on the market'. This is the key moment. It signals to everyone in the room that the property will sell. From this point, the highest bidder when the hammer falls will buy the property unconditionally. There is no cooling-off period for auction sales in Queensland. Contracts are exchanged on the spot.</p>

      <p>After the 'on the market' declaration, bidding often accelerates. Buyers who had been holding back may now commit, knowing the property will definitely sell. Your agent may give you an update at this point if you are waiting nearby.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If bidding stalls below the reserve</h2>
      <p>Sometimes bidding reaches a plateau before the reserve. The auctioneer may pause, call for higher bids, and use their experience to draw out reluctant bidders. Your agent may consult you privately during this pause about whether to adjust the reserve downward or hold firm. This is a real-time decision with real consequences: hold too firm and the property may pass in; drop the reserve too readily and you may leave money on the table if a higher bid was coming.</p>

      <p>If there is only one registered bidder, the property effectively cannot auction competitively. The auctioneer may still proceed and use vendor bids, but the dynamics are different, and your agent should have spoken with you before auction day about this scenario.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If the property passes in</h2>
      <p>If bidding does not reach the reserve when the auctioneer calls the property, it is passed in. The highest bidder, if there was one, gets the first right to negotiate with you privately after the auction. Your agent should move that buyer and their representative into a private space immediately after the gavel comes down, while the moment is still fresh and the buyer is still emotionally engaged.</p>

      <p>Passing in is not a failed sale. A significant proportion of Brisbane auction properties are negotiated to a contract within hours of being passed in. What it does mean is that the market told you something during the campaign: either the price guide was too high, the property attracted interest but not conviction, or the conditions on the day were against you. Your agent should debrief you honestly on which of these it was.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">After the hammer falls</h2>
      <p>If the property sells under the hammer, both parties sign contracts immediately. The buyer typically pays a deposit on the day, as specified in the auction terms. There is no cooling-off period. The contract is binding. Your agent will guide both parties through the paperwork, and your solicitor or conveyancer takes over from there.</p>

      <p>As a seller in that moment, the key thing to know is that the outcome is locked in. The price achieved is the price. From here, the process moves to the settlement period specified in the contract, typically 30 to 60 days.</p>

